<p>We have seen the summarized article <i>"monad in programming"</i> in the previous post.</p><p>Let's find out what is a monad in category theory and how the concept became relevant for functional programming.</p><p>First, we need to understand the basics of category theory.</p><p><b>Category</b> <br /></p><p>A category consists of objects and morphisms (relationships) between those objects. More of it, the morphisms should be composable too.</p><p>Below is an example of a category.</p><p><img alt="" height="272" src="data:image/png;base64," width="281" /></p><p>Each dot is an object and each arrow shows morphism from some object to another. As arrows are composable, if there is a morphism from object <i>a</i> to object <i>b</i>, and there is another morphism from <i>b</i> to <i>c</i>, then we can find a morphism from <i>a</i> to <i>c</i>.&nbsp;</p><p><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /> <br /></p><p>If you notice, there is <i>identity</i> morphism too, it exists for each object, but we have shown it just for <i>x</i>. The second type of endofunctor is also known as identity functor.&nbsp;</p><p><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /> <br /></p><p>We have shown here two endofunctors.&nbsp; <i>I<sub>C</sub></i> is an identity functor and <i>E</i> is an endofunctor that maps <i>a</i> to <i>Ea</i>, <i>b</i> to <i>Eb</i>, and <i>f</i> to <i>Ef</i> in the same category.<br /></p><p><b>Natural transformation</b></p><p>Natural transformation is a relationship between functors.<br /></p><p>Suppose, there are two functors <i>F</i> and <i>G</i> from<b> </b>category <i>C</i> to <i>D</i>. <br /></p><p><img alt="" height="294" src="data:image/png;base64," width="629" /> <br /></p><p>&nbsp;We get below morphisms in category <i>D</i>.</p><p><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><p>Natural transformation exists if we could find some morphism components of the transformation in the target category.</p><p>If we could find out morphisms from&nbsp; <i>Fa</i> to <i>Gb</i>, we can say that we have a natural transformation from <i>F</i> to <i>G</i>. If we have composed functor FG, we can have horizontally composed natural transformation <span style="font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; font-style: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;"></span><span style="font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;"> </span><span style="font-style: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;">?</span><span style="font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;">&nbsp;</span><span style="font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;"> </span><span style="font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; font-style: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;">a.</span> <br /></p><p><img alt="" height="300" src="data:image/png;base64," width="424" /></p><p>Now, let's consider category <i>D</i>.</p><p><img alt="" height="321" src="data:image/png;base64," width="511" /></p><p>Here, we want to define morphism from <i>FGy</i> to <i>y</i>.
